column59:
During the election Immigration was an important issue. 

In the start of 2022 Russia lanched a military invasion of Ukraine which resulted in a big amount of ukrainian immigrants in big parts of europe.

Denmark received a lot of immigrants from Ukraine during 2022.

The topic of immigration has typically been focused on immigrants from the middle east and northern Africa but the Russian invasion of Ukraine changed this. 

The government accepted a lot more ukrainian immigrants than what is typical for the danish government, starting a discussion about why ukrainian immigrants were more "worthy" of receiving help than immigrants from other countries outside of europe.

column31:
I am kind of confused as to what to do?

When i inspect how the evolution of how many respondents weigh "environment" as the most important subject develops across the election campaign, I look at the mean of "agendaEnvironment".

At the first date of the election campaign, the 5th of October 2022, the mean for "agendaEnvironment" is at 0.1245902

At the last date (31th of October 2022), the mean is at 0.1574344

This suggests that the further into the campaign, the more people weigh environmental issues as being important for them – although it doesn't conclude statistical significant, it seems to rise across the whole campaign, whilst going up and down throughout the whole campaign.

It seems to rise a small amount, not a lot.

column59:
The four variables measure health, environment, immigration and economy, showing whether participants saw each of the issues at the most important political one (1=yes, 0=no)

I made a plot with the data concerning "Immigration on the agenda during the 2022 Danish election campaign". It shows a high mention of immigrants in the beginning (about 50) in the start of the campaign. After that is significantly drops during the mid-campaign from about the 5th of October until the 25th. The mention of immigration experience short spikes, but doesn't get mentioned nearly as much as in the beginning until about the 25th-26th of October. 

This suggest that immigration was a big topic in the beginning and the end, but lost some salience as the campaign progressed and other topics might have taken up more space.
